  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's something I've seen play out in the community I know. Growing up in a working-class family in Philadelphia, my dad worked construction and my mom had a master's in education, but neither of us went far beyond vocational training or a high school diploma. I've seen students from similar backgrounds, especially girls and minority kids, freeze up during math tests because they're worried about being seen as 'less capable.' That anxiety isn't just about the test—it's about the fear of confirming a stereotype that they're not smart enough for STEM. I think we absolutely should address it, but not with big, expensive programs. Real change starts with simple things: teachers who talk openly about how everyone learns at different paces, parents who encourage kids to try without fear of failure, and workplaces that don't make it seem like STEM is only for 'the smart ones.' My own experience as a cleaner—where I've spent years fixing things and solving problems—makes me realize that skills matter more than labels. We need to stop saying 'you're not cut out for this' and start saying 'let's figure this out together.' It's not about changing the system overnight; it's about building trust, one conversation at a time.",
